  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "The image processing routine for analyzing dendritic spines involves a five-step pipeline: (i) data pre-processing as described before, (ii) spine location detection, (iii) segmentation to isolate them, (iv) quantification of morphological characteristics, and (v) classification or clustering based on their morphology (Li et al., 2023).",
    "The primary objective in the spine detection phase is the precise identification of individual entities' locations within the 3D image (Rodriguez et al., 2008).",
    "This process begins delineating dendrite boundaries, utilizing information extracted from the dendrite 3D mesh (Mukai et al., 2011; Okabe, 2020).",
    "There are four main spine detection automatic approaches.",
    "The most prevalent method is skeletonization, which involves the removal of consecutive layers of pixels from the dendritic boundary (Okabe, 2020)."
  ],
